		<div id="siteNotice"><script type='text/javascript'>if (wgNotice != '') document.writeln(wgNotice);</script></div>		<h1 id="firstHeading" class="firstHeading">Growth-share matrix</h1>
		<div id="bodyContent">
			<h3 id="siteSub">From Wikipedia, the free encyclopedia</h3>
			<div id="contentSub"></div>
									<div id="jump-to-nav">Jump to: <a href="#column-one">navigation</a>, <a href="#searchInput">search</a></div>			<!-- start content -->
			<p>The <b>BCG matrix</b> (aka B.C.G. analysis, BCG-matrix, Boston Box, Boston Matrix, <a href="/wiki/Boston_Consulting_Group" title="Boston Consulting Group">Boston Consulting Group</a> analysis) is a chart that had been created by Bruce Henderson for the <a href="/wiki/Boston_Consulting_Group" title="Boston Consulting Group">Boston Consulting Group</a> in 1970 to help <a href="/wiki/Corporation" title="Corporation">corporations</a> with analyzing their <a href="/wiki/Business" title="Business">business</a> units or <a href="/wiki/Product_line" title="Product line" class="mw-redirect">product lines</a>. This helps the company allocate resources and is used as an analytical tool in <a href="/wiki/Brand" title="Brand">brand marketing</a>, <a href="/wiki/Product_management" title="Product management">product management</a>, <a href="/wiki/Strategic_management" title="Strategic management">strategic management</a>, and <a href="/wiki/Portfolio_(finance)" title="Portfolio (finance)">portfolio analysis</a>.<sup class="noprint Template-Fact"><span title="This claim needs references to reliable sources&#160;since February 2009" style="white-space: nowrap;">[<i><a href="/wiki/Wikipedia:Citation_needed" title="Wikipedia:Citation needed">citation needed</a></i>]</span></sup></p>
<table id="toc" class="toc" summary="Contents">
